<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The genus 
<taxonomicName family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Lepidochaetus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lepidochaetus" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="genus">Lepidochaetus</taxonomicName>
was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kisielewski, J" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1 - 168" title="Inland-water Gastrotricha from Brazil." volume="43" year="1991">Kisielewski (1991)</bibRefCitation>
to group some 
<taxonomicName family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chaetonotus" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="genus">Chaetonotus</taxonomicName>
species characterized by numerous, rounded, unkeeled 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="6" start="start">scales</pageBreakToken>
, provided with long and thin spines covering both the dorsal and the ventral body surfaces. However, here we follow 
<bibRefCitation author="Balsamo, M" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 19" title="Taxonomic and nomenclatural notes on freshwater Gastrotricha" volume="2158" year="2009">Balsamo et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
who considered this taxon as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chaetonotus" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="genus">Chaetonotus</taxonomicName>
. Our specimens resemble 
<taxonomicName family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chaetonotus (Lepidochaetus) brasilianus" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="brasilianus" subGenus="Lepidochaetus">Chaetonotus (Lepidochaetus) brasilianus</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kisielewski, J" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1 - 168" title="Inland-water Gastrotricha from Brazil." volume="43" year="1991">Kisielewski 1991</bibRefCitation>
), due a similar scale shape and distribution, and rearmost lateral spines arranged in three pairs, which gradually grow in length in a caudal direction. However, they can be distinguished from the previously described species by the absence of cuticular rods and the neck sensorial bristles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
